<a href="javascript:card_browser(116)">The Pale Blade</a> x2 <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(113)">Nazgul Sword</a> <br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(103)">Black Breath</a> x4 <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(104)">Blade Tip</a> x2 <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(130)">Wreathed in Shadow</a> x2 <br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(112)">Morgul Gates</a> x3 <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(106)">Dark Whispers</a> x2 <br>
<br>
<br>
  </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <br>
Strategy  <br>
<br>
This deck is very different from many of the most common decks out there. In fact, it relentlessly exploits the trends in current deck designs and is almost unbeatable. <br>
<br>
The most basic principle is that you are giving away almost no pool. At first glance it may seem that you would be easily overwhelmed by numerous minions, but this never *ever* happens in reality. Even the swarming moria orc decks cannot muster enough guys to get through your defenses (it would take about 6 guys or so - not 3, as I will explain). Uruks can forget it, they won&#39;t be able to get down enough guys to hurt you and Aragorn slaughters these guys better than in the movie. Same goes for Sauron Orcs, who generally don&#39;t even bother to play the game until site 6 plus since you give no pool. Nazgul are a bit better, but Aragorn handles them well and they&#39;ll never get 2 out at once so you&#39;re fine. <br>
<br>
How it Works: <br>
<br>
&quot;You have to learn *why things work* on a starship&quot; - Captain Kirk <br>
<br>
The deck begins to assault your opponent from the very first decision point. You should bid 4 burdens. This puts a decision to your opponent (though he does not know it) - bid 4+ and face the Nazgul from hell, or let you go first. If you go first, it&#39;s no Prancing Pony for them and you get the Gaffer (a nice but not required bonus). If they were planning on the Prancing Pony start then it&#39;s Screwsville, population you. The key here is to recognize that if they do not go first and you are able to go 2 sites even once (say the first move), then your opponent must go 2 sites *3 times* in the game to win. They will get absolutely crushed by Nazgul trying to do this! <br>
<br>
The second important deck concept this that Frodo is not hiding in the corner! In fact, he&#39;s kicking your butt. Sting makes him easily able to fight without being overwhelmed. Hobbit Stealth evades trolls and battles where 2 guys go after Frodo (rare). Sting lets you look to see when it&#39;s a good time to go twice (the best benefit), as well as just saying no to orc swarms. Power of Stature gets you out of more jams than you could imagine and is another nail in the coffin of Moria decks. Frodo earns every bit of that one pool it takes to move him, and that&#39;s the key to the efficiency of the deck. <br>
<br>
Aragorn&#39;s role <br>
<br>
You make this guy into a wrecker of worlds. He can handle anything or anybody. He can fight three guys and take one wound. He can kill huge guys. He can take it for the team. His defender+1 saves you. His equipment and support cards cost almost nothing (unlike Gandalf). He&#39;s a machine. Chicks dig him. <br>
<br>
Here comes a shocker - you don&#39;t need archery! Though Aragorn&#39;s Bow helps when you have it and augments Ranger Versatility and Power of Stature to ridiculous levels of goodness. <br>
<br>
<br>
Now some specific card choices. <br>
<br>
The Gaffer : This guy is just great with the rare Frodo. This guy carries Frodo&#39;s beer for him. Hey look, I&#39;m using Sting for free. No, you can&#39;t see *my* cards. <br>
<br>
Able Guide / No Stranger / Sting (again): I&#39;m going 2 sites now. Yes, I know it will work. No, you just sit there. No, the Gaffer will not bring you a beer. <br>
<br>
Dagger Strike: Did you see the movie? This wrecks Lurtz in the game too! Great against Nazgul , Uruks, and any big guy since it makes you damage 3 (or more if you play multiple copies). Frodo can use it too! <br>
<br>
Saga of Elendil: very versatile. Aragorn gets 4 shots on the bow. You won&#39;t need it, but hey it&#39;s good. <br>
<br>
The Shadow: <br>
<br>
Nazgul are incredible with this deck. Why? Because the Nazgul are big stop signs in black cloaks. Simply deploying one usually results in two wounds and stops the opponent in his tracks. Deploying two kills some guy for sure. Deploying three would kill everyone for sure :) <br>
<br>
In order to win a single skirmish against a Nazgul, the opponent will almost certainly be required to play an event. They won&#39;t always have one. Nazgul have enough power to beat virtually every companion. They have enough vitality to sustain archery fire. Fierce skirmishes are like auto-wounds, the opponent just can&#39;t find enough cards to keep from getting their hiney kicked. Roaming number of three = no free double move from the start. Bree Streets and Ford of Bruinen make sure of that. <br>
<br>
Black Breath: The cornerstone card. All those auto-wounds just keep building up. Even if they cancel it somehow, hey, more pool to put out more Nazgul. <br>
<br>
Blade Tip: Useful, but not as good as Black Breath. Hence, only two in the deck. <br>
<br>
To reiterate the opponent&#39;s dilemma, if they&#39;re behind, then they&#39;ll never catch up. If they go first, then they get crushed at the Ford, and then they&#39;re behind. <br>
<br>
Shadow Card Choices <br>
<br>
The Witch-King/Pale Blade: Kicks your hiney if you give me a lot of pool. <br>
<br>
Ulaire Attea: Kicks your ass. <br>
<br>
Ulaire Enquea: Kicks your hiney if you have a lot of companions or burdens. See bidding strategy above. Laughs at archery. <br>
<br>
Ulaire Nelya: Kicks your hiney when he converts Site 3 to the Ford of Bruinen. <br>
<br>
Ulaire Cantea: Got a sword? He kicked your sword&#39;s ass. Then he kicked your ass. <br>
<br>
Ulaire Toldea: Got four burdens? He kicked Legolas&#39; ass. <br>
<br>
Wreathed in Shadow: Archery decks can forget it, or exert to wound, I don&#39;t care. <br>
<br>
Morgul Gates: Sick, Jessy, sick sick sick. <br>
<br>
Dark Whispers: See bidding strategy. If you&#39;re not too far behind to catch up, you&#39;re dead. <br>
<br>
<br>
That&#39;s about it. The track record for the deck has been excellent. It wins about 98% of the games. It has never lost by having the opponent reach Site 9 ahead of me. Frodo has killed the Cave Troll. Aragorn has fought four Orcs and lived. The Nazgul have destroyed entire parties on the first turn. What more can anyone ask for? <br>
<br>
Thanks for reading, hope you enjoy it. <br>
<br>
Steven T. Turner <br>
<br>
